&gt; It’s only easier to learn because that’s how we teach our kids. The first and most basic number is not one. It’s zero.
&gt; 
&gt; I am doing my best in teaching my kids this way but the world around has the wrong idea. We’ll see how it goes...

```function cartesian_sum(A)
    s = zero(eltype(A))
    @inbounds for m ∈ axes(A,5), l ∈ axex(A,4), k ∈ axes(A,3), j ∈ axes(A,2), i ∈ axes(A,1)
        @fastmath s += A[i,j,k,l,m]
    end
    s
end
using OffsetArrays
function cartesian_sum_zero(A)
    s = zero(eltype(A))
    Az = OffsetArray(A, OffsetArrays.Origin(0,0,0,0,0))
    @inbounds for m ∈ axes(Az,5), l ∈ axes(Az,4), k ∈ axes(Az,3), j ∈ axes(Az,2), i ∈ axes(Az,1)
        @fastmath s += Az[i,j,k,l,m]
    end
    s
end

A = rand(32,2,2,2,2);
@code_native syntax=:intel debuginfo=:none cartesian_sum(A)
@code_native syntax=:intel debuginfo=:none cartesian_sum_zero(A)
@btime cartesian_sum($A)
@btime cartesian_sum_zero($A)```

